# Actionable Representations

### The Setup

![img](data:image/png;base64,)



The *state* is the position of the pointmass. The *goal* are 2D coordinates to which the agent needs to go to.

The state space is $\mathcal{S} = [-0.6,0.6] \times [-0.6,0.6]$. The goal space is simply $\mathcal{G} = \mathcal{S}$.



### The Method

1. Train a stochastic goal-conditioned policy $\pi(\cdot \vert s,g): \mathcal{S} \times \mathcal{G} \times \mathcal{A} \to \mathbb{R}$ via RL

2. Define a distance metric between two goals $g_i,g_j$ to be
   $$
   d(s_i, s_j) = \int_{\mathcal{S}} D_{JS}(\pi(\cdot | s, g_i) \| \pi(\cdot | s, g_j)) ds
   $$
   â€‹

3. Learn a representation $\phi(g)$ that preserves these distances: 
   $$
   \|\phi(g_i)-\phi(g_j)\| = d(g_i,g_j)
   $$

### An Alternative

Instead of defining the distance to be the expectation of the Jensen-Shannon Divergence over the full state space, what if we only integrate over portions of the state space. That is mathematically, consider $S_1 \subset S$, and define
$$
d(s_i, s_j) = \int_{\mathcal{S}_1} D_{JS}(\pi(\cdot | s, g_i) \| \pi(\cdot | s, g_j)) ds
$$
Here are some plots of what this looks like when we only integrate over the top region: Notice that from the perspective of the top region, essentially all points on the bottom seem the same (which makes sense, because you require essentially the same actions to get to everything)
